### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

When an `effect()` reads both a `computed()` signal and the source signal used by that computed, the effect may execute multiple times for a single source update.

This is surprising because the dependency graph overlaps transitively, but the effect appears to be scheduled more than once.

### Minimal reproduction

```ts
const count = signal(0);

const doubled = computed(() => {
  console.log('computed runs');
  return count() * 2;
});

effect(() => {
  console.log('effect runs');
  console.log(doubled());
  console.log(count());
});

count.set(1);
```

